at puberty","10 million at 20 weeks gestation, 5 million at birth, 1 million at puberty","5 million at 20 weeks gestation, 500,000 at birth, 50,000 at puberty","1 million at 20 weeks gestation, 750,000 at birth, 250,000 at puberty"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pattern is \u003Cstrong\u003E7 million at 20 weeks gestation, 2 million at birth, 400,000 at puberty\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents the normal physiological decline in oocyte numbers throughout development and early life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect patterns are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2 million at 20 weeks gestation, 1 million at birth, 100,000 at puberty\u003C/strong\u003E - These numbers are too low at all stages\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10 million at 20 weeks gestation, 5 million at birth, 1 million at puberty\u003C/strong\u003E - These numbers are too high at all stages\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5 million at 20 weeks gestation, 500,000 at birth, 50,000 at puberty\u003C/strong\u003E - The decline is too steep and the numbers are incorrect\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1 million at 20 weeks gestation, 750,000 at birth, 250,000 at puberty\u003C/strong\u003E - These numbers are too low and the decline is too gradual\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern of decline continues throughout reproductive life, with only about 400 follicles completing development and ovulation. The remainder are lost through atresia, leading to eventual depletion at menopause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The number of primordial follicles in human ovaries peaks at 20 weeks gestation with approximately 7 million follicles.","Follicle numbers decline through atresia, with approximately 2 million present at birth and 400,000 at puberty.","By menopause, nearly all follicles have been depleted through atresia or ovulation."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T15:53:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T20:14:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11438"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79766"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:35+10